Alternative Release Scenarios
Alternative release scenarios which are considered to be more likely to occur are those which may result in the release of anywhere from less than one-pound to up to 64,000-pounds of 37-percent concentrated formaldehyde solution.  These scenarios include situations such as a pinhole leak, partial or complete failures in the formaldehyde transfer piping and/or pinhole leaks or partial failures in the formaldehyde storage tank.  In order to be conservative in the estimation of the vulnerable zone, it was assumed that 64,000-pounds of 37-percent concentrated formaldehyde solution is released during an accident involving the complete failure of a liquid transfer line from the storage tank.  In this hypothetical accidental release scenario, the transfer pump continues to transfer formaldehyde from the formaldehyde storage tank.  Eventually, the full contents of the tank (a maximum of 64,000-pounds) are spilled into the containment area surrounding the storage tank, pump and transfer lines.  Utilizing USEPA?s Offsite Consequence Analysis Guidance Reference Tables and Equati
